"""
mkt-original | Numbers 11-13 | Hebrew/Aramaic term analysis
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-numbers-11-13.py

Ch 11 (35 verses): The craving in the wilderness — mixed multitude's taˀavah;
Moses' lament; 70 elders; Spirit distributed; quail and the Graves of Craving.
Key: wayyitˀonenu (grumble, hapax), asafsuf (mixed multitude, hapax), nefesh
(soul/throat in 11:6), atsal (set apart Spirit in 11:17), Eldad/Medad prophecy,
mi-yitten kol-ˁam YHWH nˀviˀim (Moses' Pentecost prayer in 11:29).

Ch 12 (16 verses): Miriam and Aaron challenge Moses; YHWH defends Moses'
uniqueness. Key: anav (humble/meek, 12:3), neˀeman bˀkhol-beiti (faithful in
all my house, 12:7 — cited verbatim in Heb 3:2,5), peh-ˀel-peh (mouth to mouth,
12:8), temunat YHWH (the form of YHWH, 12:8), Moses' concise prayer (12:13).

Ch 13 (33 verses): The 12 spies; Joshua's name change (Hoshea → Yehoshua = Jesus);
the Eshcol cluster; the grasshopper report vs. Caleb's faith; Nephilim/Anakim.
Key: Hoshea → Yehoshua (13:16, the name of Jesus), ˁaloh naˁaleh (Caleb's emphatic
ascent, 13:30), Nephilim/ḥagavim (grasshoppers, 13:33).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent


def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}


def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f"  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}")


def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html


NUMBERS = {
    "11": {
        "1": "<p><span class='term'>wayyitˀonenu</span> (וַיִּתְאֹנְנוּ) — a rare verb from the root <em>ˀanan</em>, appearing only here. The form is reflexive-intensive (hitpaˁel): they brought complaint against themselves and against God. The LXX renders it <em>egoggyzan</em> (grumbled), the same word Paul uses for the wilderness generation in 1 Cor 10:10. The fire at Taberah is YHWH's immediate judgment — no mediating cause, just direct divine response to the first sound of complaint.</p>",
        "2": "<p><span class='term'>wayyitpallel</span> (וַיִּתְפַּלֵּל) — Moses prayed (hitpaˁel of palal = to intervene, judge). Moses' intercession stops the fire. The pattern repeats throughout Numbers: Israel sins → YHWH judges → Moses intercedes → judgment stops. Moses functions as the structural type of the one mediator (1 Tim 2:5) who stands in the gap between a holy God and a sinning people.</p>",
        "3": "<p><span class='term'>Tabˁerah</span> (תַּבְעֵרָה) — from <em>baˁar</em> (to burn, consume). The place receives its name from the event. The wilderness journey is narrated through its place names: each toponym encodes a theological moment. The landscape of Israel's failure becomes a lasting geography of warning.</p>",
        "4": "<p><span class='term'>asafsuf</span> (אַסַפְסֻף) — hapax; from <em>asaph</em> (to gather). The 'mixed multitude' (cf. Exod 12:38, ˁerev rav) who joined Israel from Egypt. Their craving (<span class='term'>wayyitˀavvu taˀavah</span>, וַיִּתְאַוּוּ תַּאֲוָה) is a figura etymologica: 'they craved a craving' — an intensified desire named by the root itself. The place Kibroth-hattaˀavah (v.34) preserves the vocabulary: <em>taˀavah</em> = craving, desire, lust.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The list of Egyptian foods mourned — fish, cucumbers, melons, leeks, onions, garlic — is a memory of Egypt as <em>provision without cost</em>: <span class='term'>ḥinnam</span> (חִנָּם, free of charge). The irony is sharp: Egyptian labor was as far from free as any servitude could be. The memory of the slave diet has been filtered through craving into a fantasy of abundance. Craving distorts memory.</p>",
        "6": "<p><span class='term'>naphshenu yˁveshah</span> (נַפְשֵׁנוּ יְבֵשָׁה) — 'our nefesh is parched/withered.' <em>Nefesh</em> here carries its primary physiological meaning (throat, gullet, the organ of desire and hunger) — their very swallowing apparatus has dried up. The complaint is that manna satisfies nothing: <span class='term'>ein kol</span> (אֵין כֹּל, there is nothing at all) — total dissatisfaction. The manna provided fully; the dissatisfaction was in the nefesh, not in the provision.</p>",
        "7": "<p><span class='term'>mann hu</span> (מָן הוּא) — 'what is it?' The popular etymology of <em>manna</em>. The description: like <span class='term'>zeraˁ gad</span> (coriander seed, זֶרַע גַּד) and its color like <span class='term'>keˁen haˀbdolaḥ</span> (bdellium resin, בְּדֹלַח — also mentioned in Gen 2:12 in the description of Eden's materials). The manna has an Edenic quality — a provision from the garden-state of the world.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The people <span class='term'>shoṭetu</span> (שָׁטְטוּ, traveled around gathering it) and ground it in mills or beat it in mortars. The description of manna preparation emphasizes the labor involved in receiving the gift. God's provision still requires human participation. The manna was not ready-cooked; it was material requiring transformation. Jesus' self-identification as the true bread from heaven (John 6:31-35) interprets Num 11:7-8.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The manna fell with the dew: <span class='term'>biˀredet hatal</span> (בְּרֶדֶת הַטָּל) — 'in the falling of the dew.' Dew in the OT is a symbol of divine blessing descending quietly overnight (Deut 32:2; Ps 133:3; Prov 19:12). The manna arrives exactly as blessing arrives: silently, nightly, without human observation or effort. The morning reveals what God has done in the dark.</p>",
        "10": "<p><span class='term'>bˁozen YHWH</span> (בְּאָזְנֵי יְהוָה) — 'in the ears of the LORD' (v.1). YHWH's hearing of the complaint is not metaphorical; the text is anthropomorphic and deliberate. The cry reaches the divine ear and kindles the divine anger (<span class='term'>wayˀiḥar ˀap-YHWH</span>). Moses' distress at being caught between YHWH's anger and the people's weeping is the condition of the intercessor.</p>",
        "11": "<p>Moses uses the language of <span class='term'>raˁah</span> (רָעָה, evil/trouble): 'Why have you brought evil/trouble on your servant?' The intercessor is allowed frank speech — even accusatory speech — toward God. The same vocabulary of divine burden-shifting appears in the Psalms of lament. Moses' complaint in vv.11-15 is a model of honest prayer that does not mask difficulty with pious language.</p>",
        "12": "<p><span class='term'>heˀerothi</span> (הֶאֱרִיתִי) — 'did I conceive them?' From <em>harah</em> (to conceive, be pregnant). Moses refuses the nursing-father role: <span class='term'>kˀˀomen</span> (כָּאֹמֵן, as a guardian/nurse, sometimes 'foster-father') — the same root gives <em>emunah</em> (faithfulness/trust) and <em>ˀamen</em>. The paradox: the root for nursing/trustworthy is also the root for the ultimate theological affirmation. Moses denies being Israel's ˀomen; Christ is Israel's ˀomen in the deepest sense (Heb 3:2: <em>pistos</em>, faithful).</p>",
        "13": "<p><span class='term'>mayyin asher-ˀeten</span> (מֵאַיִן) — 'where am I to get?' The impossible demand: meat for six hundred thousand. Moses' lament exposes the mathematical absurdity of the people's demand. The provision that follows will be miraculous precisely because human calculation shows it impossible. God's generosity routinely outstrips human mathematics.</p>",
        "14": "<p><span class='term'>loˀ ˀukal ˀanochi levadi</span> (לֹא אוּכַל אָנֹכִי לְבַדִּי) — 'I am not able — I alone.' The leadership crisis: one person cannot bear the whole people. The solution (70 elders sharing the Spirit) is the wilderness precursor of the apostolic commissioning, and ultimately of the Spirit poured out on all flesh (Joel 2:28). The inability of one person to bear God's people alone anticipates the communal structure of the Spirit.</p>",
        "15": "<p>Moses' extreme prayer: kill me right now (<span class='term'>harog-ni naˀ harog</span>) if I have found favor. The conditional favor-and-death request is dark; it mirrors Elijah's suicidal prayer (1 Kgs 19:4). But both requests are met with provision and renewed commission rather than death. The servant who asks for death at the breaking point receives instead the power to continue.</p>",
        "16": "<p><span class='term'>ziqne Yisraˀel</span> (זִקְנֵי יִשְׂרָאֵל, elders of Israel) — seventy men who serve as Israel's governing council. The number 70 recurs: 70 elders on Sinai (Exod 24:1), 70 nations in the Table of Nations (Gen 10), 70 members of the later Sanhedrin. The number signifies totality and representativeness. What Moses cannot do alone, seventy representatives can share.</p>",
        "17": "<p><span class='term'>weˀatsalthi</span> (וְאָצַלְתִּי) — from <em>atsal</em> (to set aside, set apart, withhold). YHWH will take from the ruaḥ (Spirit) that is on Moses and set a portion on the elders. The Spirit is not diminished in Moses by this distribution — unlike a finite physical substance, the Spirit's apportionment does not reduce the source. The Pentecost event (Acts 2) is the eschatological fulfillment: the Spirit poured out on all flesh, drawn from the inexhaustible source of the risen Christ.</p>",
        "18": "<p><span class='term'>hitqaddˀshu</span> (הִתְקַדְּשׁוּ, consecrate yourselves) — qal reflexive (hitpaˁel) of <em>qadash</em>. The required preparation before meat: a day of consecration. The demand for meat will be met, but not before consecration. YHWH's giving of what is asked sometimes requires preparation that underscores the giver's holiness rather than merely satisfying the demand.</p>",
        "19": "<p>The emphatic negative list — not one day, not two, not five, not ten, not twenty days — builds toward the judgment-provision of v.20. The repetition enacts the escalation of divine sarcasm: YHWH will give them exactly what they demanded, in excess. The rhetoric of the list makes the irony unavoidable before the punchline lands.</p>",
        "20": "<p><span class='term'>meˀastem ˀet-YHWH</span> (מְאַסְתֶּם אֶת-יְהוָה) — 'you have rejected/despised the LORD who is among you.' The root <em>maˀas</em> = to reject, despise. Israel has not merely complained about food; they have rejected the one who provided it. The theological movement: dissatisfaction with provision → rejection of the provider. The manna was the daily visible presence of YHWH's care; refusing it was refusing him.</p>",
        "21": "<p><span class='term'>shesh-meˀot ˀelef ragli</span> (שֵׁשׁ-מֵאוֹת אֶלֶף רַגְלִי) — six hundred thousand foot soldiers. Moses replicates the people's doubt in mathematical form: how can God feed this many? The number itself is the expression of impossibility. YHWH's response (v.23: <span class='term'>hayad YHWH tiqtsaˀr?</span> — 'Is the hand of YHWH too short?') is the theological counter to all arithmetic of impossibility.</p>",
        "22": "<p>The rhetorical questions: would all the flocks and herds suffice? Would all the fish of the sea? Moses enumerates every natural category of provision and declares each insufficient. YHWH answers none of the specific questions; he simply asks whether his hand is short. The divine answer to 'how is this possible?' is not an explanation but a question about the questioner's theology of God's power.</p>",
        "23": "<p><span class='term'>hayad YHWH tiqtsaˀr?</span> (הֲיַד יְהוָה תִּקְצָר?) — 'Is the hand of the LORD too short?' <em>Yad</em> (hand) = power, agency. <em>qatsar</em> (to be short, insufficient). The same phrase appears in Isa 59:1: 'The LORD's hand is not too short to save.' The wilderness question is answered definitively at the cross: the hand of YHWH that could not be shortened reaches all the way to death and back.</p>",
        "24": "<p>Moses gathers seventy elders and stations them around the tent. The spatial arrangement matters: the tent is the center of the Spirit's distribution. The elders are not gathered in Moses' home or in a place of their choosing; the Spirit is given from where YHWH is. Proximity to the divine presence is the condition of the Spirit's gift.</p>",
        "25": "<p><span class='term'>wayyitnabeˀu</span> (וַיִּתְנַבְּאוּ) — they prophesied (hitpaˁel of <em>navaˀ</em>). The Spirit came on them and they prophesied — but they <span class='term'>loˀ yasafu</span> (לֹא יָסָפוּ, did not continue/add). The prophetic experience was one-time, not permanent. The elder council receives an initial Spirit-endowment for leadership, not the ongoing prophetic gift. The distinction between occasional and permanent spiritual empowerment runs through the OT.</p>",
        "26": "<p>Eldad and Medad had remained in the camp (<span class='term'>wayyishshaˀaru bammaḥaneh</span>). The Spirit did not wait for them to come to the tent; it found them where they were. The spatial theology of Num 11:26 is a wilderness precedent for the Spirit's freedom: it blows where it wills (John 3:8). Geographic or institutional non-attendance does not limit the Spirit's reach.</p>",
        "27": "<p>The report runs to Moses: <span class='term'>mitnabeˀim bammaḥaneh</span> — 'prophesying in the camp!' The alarm is institutional anxiety: prophetic activity was expected to occur at the tent under proper oversight. The wilderness situation of uncontrolled Spirit-distribution anticipates Paul's management of charismatic gifts in 1 Cor 12-14, and the Pentecostal explosion beyond Jerusalem in Acts 8-10.</p>",
        "28": "<p>Joshua's complaint: <span class='term'>kˀleˀem</span> (כְּלָאֵם, stop them / restrain them). Joshua is protecting Moses' unique prophetic office. His concern is institutional rather than theological: if everyone prophesies, what becomes of Moses' special status? Moses' response exposes the poverty of this thinking: real spiritual leadership wants others to exceed itself.</p>",
        "29": "<p><span class='term'>mi-yitten kol-ˁam YHWH nˀviˀim</span> (מִי יִתֵּן כָּל-עַם יְהוָה נְבִיאִים) — 'Oh that all the LORD's people were prophets!' Moses' deepest wish: the democratization of the Spirit. The optative <em>mi-yitten</em> (who will give?) is the wishful idiom of desire. Joel 2:28-29 promises that this will happen: 'I will pour out my Spirit on all flesh... your sons and daughters will prophesy.' Acts 2:17 declares it fulfilled. The Mosaic wish is the Pentecost prophecy.</p>",
        "30": "<p>Moses and the elders returned to the camp. The Spirit's distribution complete, ordinary communal life resumes. The Spirit is not incompatible with ordinary leadership and daily life; the prophetic eruption at the tent was an event, not a permanent disruption of order.</p>",
        "31": "<p><span class='term'>ruaḥ nasaˁ meˀet YHWH</span> (רוּחַ נָסַע מֵאֵת יְהוָה) — 'a wind/spirit went out from YHWH.' The same word <em>ruaḥ</em> (spirit/wind) used for the Spirit on the elders now describes the wind bringing the quail. The word play is probably intentional: YHWH sends both kinds of ruaḥ — the Spirit of prophecy and the wind of provision. Both are from him; both reveal his power.</p>",
        "32": "<p>The people gather quail obsessively: all day, all night, all the next day. The one who gathered least took ten homers (a homer ≈ 220 liters). The excess enacts the judgment-gift: YHWH will give them what they demand until they are sick of it (v.20). Ungoverned craving receives exactly what it wants, in exactly the form it should have feared.</p>",
        "33": "<p><span class='term'>habbaser ˁod ben shinneyhem</span> (הַבָּשָׂר עוֹד בֵּין שִׁנֵּיהֶם) — 'the meat was still between their teeth.' The judgment fell before the first meal was finished. The speed of divine response to presumptuous consumption underscores that YHWH's patience had already been exhausted before the quail arrived. The anger was latent in the giving; the gift was already a judgment.</p>",
        "34": "<p><span class='term'>Qivroth-hattaˀavah</span> (קִבְרוֹת הַתַּאֲוָה) — 'Graves of the Craving/Desire.' The place where the people buried those struck by plague. The etymology becomes the epitaph: where craving ruled, burial follows. The naming of places in Israel's wilderness journey serves as a theological mnemonic — the landscape teaches the theology of sin and consequence.</p>",
        "35": "<p>The itinerary resumes: from Kibroth-hattaavah to Hazeroth. The wilderness journey continues immediately after burial. Israel does not stop to process; the march goes on. The relentlessness of the wilderness journey is itself part of the formation: there is no settling down in a place of failure, no permanent dwelling in the graves of desire.</p>",
    },
    "12": {
        "1": "<p><span class='term'>ˀal-ˀodot</span> (עַל-אֹדוֹת, concerning/because of) + <span class='term'>ˀisha Kushit</span> (אִשָּׁה כֻשִׁית, the Cushite woman). The complaint is ostensibly about Moses' foreign wife but functions as a pretext for challenging his authority (v.2). <em>Kush</em> usually refers to Ethiopia/Nubia; this may be Zipporah (Ex 2:21, from Midian) or a second wife. The specific identity matters less than the target: Moses' unique mediatorial position.</p>",
        "2": "<p><span class='term'>raq-bˀmoshe dibber YHWH?</span> (הֲרַק אַךְ-בְּמֹשֶׁה דִּבֶּר יְהוָה) — 'Has the LORD spoken only through Moses?' The challenge to prophetic monopoly is a claim for equal standing. But the end of the verse is chilling: <span class='term'>wayishmaˁ YHWH</span> (וַיִּשְׁמַע יְהוָה, 'and YHWH heard it'). The challenge that seems to widen prophetic access inadvertently invites divine adjudication of the claim.</p>",
        "3": "<p><span class='term'>wehˀish Mosheh ˁanav meˀod</span> (וְהָאִישׁ מֹשֶׁה עָנָו מְאֹד) — 'And the man Moses was very humble/meek, more than any person on the face of the earth.' <em>ˁAnav</em> (עָנָו) = meek, humble, poor in spirit. This is the narrator's parenthetical defense of Moses: his non-response to the attack was not weakness but the most profound meekness. Jesus cites this attribute for himself: 'I am meek (<em>praus</em>) and lowly in heart' (Matt 11:29); he blesses 'the meek' (<em>praus</em>) in Matt 5:5. The description of Moses is the background text for Jesus' self-description.</p>",
        "4": "<p>YHWH calls all three — Moses, Aaron, Miriam — to the tent of meeting: <span class='term'>tsˀu shloshtekem</span> (צְאוּ שְׁלָשְׁתְּכֶם, go out, you three). The summons is sovereign; the disputants do not come on their own initiative. When divine authority is at stake, YHWH settles the matter directly rather than leaving it to human deliberation.</p>",
        "5": "<p>YHWH descends in a pillar of cloud and stands at the tent entrance: <span class='term'>ˁamud heˁanan</span> (עַמּוּד הֶעָנָן, pillar of cloud). The theophanic presence is the visual guarantee of what follows. The cloud column that guided Israel through the wilderness now serves as the venue for the judgment of prophetic claims. The same presence that guides also adjudicates.</p>",
        "6": "<p><span class='term'>im-yihyeh nˀviˀakhem YHWH</span> — if there is a prophet among you, YHWH makes himself known in <span class='term'>marˀah</span> (מַרְאָה, vision) and speaks in <span class='term'>ḥalom</span> (חֲלוֹם, dream). These are the two standard modes of prophetic revelation for ordinary prophets: visual and nocturnal. The distinction in vv.6-8 establishes a three-tiered prophetic epistemology: ordinary prophets (dream/vision), Moses (face to face, form seen), and YHWH himself.</p>",
        "7": "<p><span class='term'>loˀ-ken ˁavdi Mosheh / bˀkhol-beiti neˀeman huˀ</span> (לֹא-כֵן עַבְדִּי מֹשֶׁה / בְּכָל-בֵּיתִי נֶאֱמָן הוּא) — 'Not so my servant Moses; he is faithful in all my house.' <em>Neˀeman</em> = faithful, trustworthy (niphˁal of <em>ˀaman</em>). The Epistle to the Hebrews cites this directly: 'Moses was faithful (<em>pistos</em>) in all God's house' (Heb 3:2,5) in order to contrast Moses' faithfulness as a <em>servant</em> with Christ's faithfulness as the <em>Son</em> over the house. The verse is the biblical foundation for the Moses/Christ typology in Hebrews 3.</p>",
        "8": "<p><span class='term'>peh ˀel-peh adabber-bo</span> (פֶּה אֶל-פֶּה אֲדַבֶּר-בּוֹ) — 'mouth to mouth I speak with him.' Direct, unmediated speech — not in visions or dreams but face to face. <span class='term'>utemunat YHWH yabit</span> (וּתְמֻנַת יְהוָה יַבִּיט) — 'he sees the form/figure of YHWH.' <em>Temunah</em> = shape, form, figure. The same word appears in Deut 4:12,15 where Israel saw no form at Sinai. Moses saw what Israel was forbidden to make an image of. His unique access to the divine form is both his privilege and his responsibility.</p>",
        "9": "<p><span class='term'>wayˀiḥar-ˀap YHWH</span> (וַיֶּחֱרִי-אַף יְהוָה) — the anger of YHWH blazed and he departed (<span class='term'>wayyelek</span>). The divine departure is itself a judgment. When YHWH leaves, the protection of his presence leaves with him. The cloud rising from Miriam is not just withdrawal of blessing — it is the unmasking of disease that the cloud's presence had held in check.</p>",
        "10": "<p><span class='term'>mesoraˁat kashsaleg</span> (מְצֹרַעַת כַּשָּׁלֶג, leprous as snow). The tsaraˁat (skin disease) strikes Miriam white as snow — the color associated with bleached death rather than purity here. The irony: the one who challenged Moses' authority over a woman (his Cushite wife) is struck with the mark that most fully embodies exclusion and marginalization. The punishment mirrors the accusation.</p>",
        "11": "<p>Aaron's confession: <span class='term'>ˀal-naˀ tashset ˁalenu ḥattaˀt</span> (אַל-נָא תָשֵׁת עָלֵינוּ חַטָּאת) — 'please do not lay on us the sin we have foolishly committed.' The word <span class='term'>noˀalnu</span> (נוֹאַלְנוּ, we have acted foolishly) is from <em>yaˀal</em> = to act foolishly/presumptuously. Aaron's intercession through Moses for Miriam is the first use of Moses' mediation by the very ones who challenged it.</p>",
        "12": "<p>Aaron's vivid plea: let her not be like a <span class='term'>met</span> (מֵת, dead one), whose flesh is half consumed when coming out of the womb — a stillborn with putrefying flesh. The graphic image (unusually visceral for biblical prose) communicates the horror of Miriam's condition: she is like a corpse that has been in the process of dissolution. The imagery draws on the connection between skin disease and death-uncleanness in Lev 13-15.</p>",
        "13": "<p><span class='term'>wayitsˁaq Mosheh ˀel-YHWH leˀmor: ˀel naˀ rfaˁ naˀ lah</span> (וַיִּצְעַק מֹשֶׁה אֶל-יְהוָה לֵאמֹר: אֵל נָא רְפָא נָא לָהּ) — 'Moses cried out to YHWH: O God, please heal her, please!' Five Hebrew words. The shortest healing prayer in Scripture. The repetition of <em>naˀ</em> (please, I beg) twice in five words concentrates urgency. Moses intercedes instantly and wholeheartedly for the woman who attacked him — a paradigm of forgiveness that precedes intercession.</p>",
        "14": "<p>YHWH's response: if her father had merely <span class='term'>yaro</span> (יָרֹק, spit) in her face, she would be in disgrace seven days — how much more now? The <em>qal waḥomer</em> (light-to-heavy argument, a fortiori): if the lesser insult requires seven days, the divine rebuke requires seven days. The seven days in Miriam's case is not purely punitive but structural: the whole community waits for her. Her authority in Israel is not destroyed but humbled and restored.</p>",
        "15": "<p><span class='term'>wehaˁam loˀ nasaˁ ˁad-heyˀaseph Miryam</span> (וְהָעָם לֹא נָסַע עַד-הֵאָסֵף מִרְיָם) — 'the people did not set out until Miriam was gathered back in.' The whole community's journey halted for her. Despite the discipline, Miriam's honor and communal belonging are preserved. The seven-day exclusion has a firm endpoint: restoration, not permanent exile. The leader who was humbled is brought back in before Israel moves on.</p>",
        "16": "<p>The itinerary verse: from Hazeroth to the wilderness of Paran. The movement continues after Miriam's restoration. The crisis of authority resolved, Israel advances toward Canaan — the next crisis awaits at the border in ch. 13. The wilderness formation alternates between provision and testing, always moving forward.</p>",
    },
    "13": {
        "1": "<p>YHWH's command to send spies: <span class='term'>shellaḥ-lˀka ˀanashim</span> (שְׁלַח-לְךָ אֲנָשִׁים) — 'send for yourself men.' The <em>lˀka</em> (לְךָ, to/for yourself) is a reflexive/middle form ('send, for your own sake/benefit'). Deuteronomy 1:22 places the initiative with the people. Both accounts are true: the people proposed; YHWH permitted. The permission accommodates human desire without guaranteeing its wisdom.</p>",
        "2": "<p><span class='term'>nˀsiˀ</span> (נָשִׂיא, leader/prince) — one from each ancestral tribe. The root <em>nasaˀ</em> = to lift, bear, carry. The leader is the one who carries the people. The etymology recurs throughout Numbers: the <em>nˀsiˀim</em> are those who bear the weight of their tribes. The twelve spies are the tribes' representative burden-bearers — their report will determine the fate of those they carry.</p>",
        "3": "<p>They were sent from <span class='term'>midbar Paran</span> (מִדְבַּר פָּארָן, wilderness of Paran). The wilderness is not merely geography; it is the theological space between promise and possession. They are sent from the wilderness toward the land — the trajectory of Israel's entire existence is contained in this mission.</p>",
        "4": "<p>The twelve names are given in vv.4-15. The list represents the full tribal structure of Israel. The spy mission is a census of trust: can all twelve tribes maintain faith at the border of the promise? The answer (two faithful, ten faithless) will determine the shape of the next forty years.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The spies from Simeon, Judah, Issachar, Ephraim, Benjamin — each listed with father's name. The patronymics ground the mission in Israel's genealogical structure. These are not anonymous agents but men with names and families, embedded in the covenant community whose future their report will determine.</p>",
        "6": "<p><span class='term'>Calev ben Yephunneh</span> (כָּלֵב בֶּן-יְפֻנֶּה) — the Calebite, from Judah. Caleb will emerge as the defining contrast to the faithless spies. His name may derive from <em>kelev</em> (dog) or from a root meaning 'heart/wholeness.' The later idiom for his faithfulness will be <span class='term'>malaˀ ˀaḥarei YHWH</span> (filled after/fully followed YHWH, 14:24) — his whole heart followed.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The spy from Issachar: Igal son of Joseph. Each tribe sends its best representative — those whom Moses knew to be leaders (11:16 used the same <em>naˀ</em> selection). The mission is the highest-stakes reconnaissance in Israel's history; the scouts are the top tier of tribal leadership.</p>",
        "8": "<p>Hoshea son of Nun from Ephraim — the man whose name will be changed in v.16. The future great leader of Israel appears in this list unremarkably, embedded among eleven others. Greatness in Israel's narrative is regularly first seen as ordinary.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The spy from Benjamin: Palti son of Raphu. The Benjaminite slot recalls the tribe that will later produce Saul (Israel's first king) and Paul (apostle to the Gentiles). Here the representative carries no such significance — he is simply one of twelve bearing the common mission.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The spy from Zebulun: Gaddiel son of Sodi. Zebulun's territory (later the tribal homeland of Jesus' Galilean ministry, Isa 9:1; Matt 4:13-16) is represented here at the moment of the great failure of nerve. The land that the Messiah will honor with his presence is scouted by those who will declare it unconquerable.</p>",
        "11": "<p>The spy from Manasseh (Joseph): Gaddi son of Susi. The Joseph tribes (Ephraim and Manasseh) each send a representative — they are counted as two half-tribes. The double portion of Joseph's inheritance is already structurally embedded in the spy roster.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The spy from Dan: Ammiel son of Gemalli. Dan will later settle in the far north (Judges 18). The scout of Dan's territory in Canaan represents a tribe whose eventual home is about as far from the Negev as possible. The whole land is being surveyed by the representative of the whole people.</p>",
        "13": "<p>The spy from Asher: Sethur son of Michael. Asher's tribal territory will include the coastal plain and the mountains of the north — among the most productive land in Canaan. The fruit the spies bring back (v.23) likely comes from areas Asher will eventually inhabit.</p>",
        "14": "<p>The spy from Naphtali: Nahbi son of Vophsi. Naphtali's territory in the north (around the Sea of Galilee) will be Zebulun's neighbor. Both are from the region Jesus will inhabit; both are scouted by men who will come back faithless.</p>",
        "15": "<p>The spy from Gad: Geuel son of Machi. Gad will ultimately settle east of the Jordan (Num 32) — ironically, Gad's representative scouts a land the tribe will choose not to inhabit. The irony threads through the spy narrative: even those who see the land's goodness may not enter it.</p>",
        "16": "<p><span class='term'>wayiqraˀ Mosheh lehosheˁa bin-Nun Yehoshuˁa</span> (וַיִּקְרָא מֹשֶׁה לְהוֹשֵׁעַ בִּן-נוּן יְהוֹשֻׁעַ) — Moses renamed Hoshea son of Nun as Joshua. <em>Hoshea</em> (הוֹשֵׁעַ) = 'salvation' (from <em>yashaˁ</em>). <em>Yehoshuˁa</em> (יְהוֹשֻׁעַ) = 'YHWH saves / YHWH is salvation' — the divine name added to the root. This is precisely the name of Jesus in Hebrew: <em>Yeshua</em> (יֵשׁוּעַ) is the contracted form of the same name. When Moses gave Joshua his name, he gave him the name of the one who would be the true leader into the true promised land.</p>",
        "17": "<p>Moses sends them into the Negev and then the hill country: <span class='term'>ˁalu zeh banNegev</span> (עֲלוּ זֶה בַנֶּגֶב). The specific directional instructions frame the scouting mission as methodical intelligence gathering — not a random wander but a systematic survey. The theological and geographical dimensions of the land are to be assessed simultaneously.</p>",
        "18": "<p><span class='term'>ureˀitem ˀet-haˀarets mah-hi</span> (וּרְאִיתֶם אֶת-הָאָרֶץ מַה-הִוא) — 'see what the land is, whether the people are strong or weak, many or few.' The spy instructions are structured as a series of questions: what is the land, what are the people, what are the cities? The survey is comprehensive — land, people, cities, soil, vegetation. The spies' failure is not that they answered incorrectly but that they drew the wrong conclusion from correct data.</p>",
        "19": "<p>The land is to be assessed: is it <span class='term'>tobah hˀ ˀim raˁah</span> (טוֹבָה הִוא אִם-רָעָה, good or bad)? <span class='term'>shamenim ˀim-razim</span> (שְׁמֵנִים אִם-רָזִים, fat/fertile or lean)? The categories are agricultural and military. Moses wants the full picture — the positive and the negative. The spies will provide exactly this; their failure is in the weight they assign to each category.</p>",
        "20": "<p><span class='term'>hˀamets ˀet-ˀanashim</span> (וְהִתְחַזַּקְתֶּם) — 'be bold' (from <em>ḥazaq</em>, to be strong). The same root as the repeated commissions to Joshua: <em>ḥazaq weˀemats</em> (be strong and courageous, Josh 1:6,7,9,18). Moses already calls them to the courage that Joshua will need to embody permanently. <span class='term'>bikkurei ˁanabim</span> (בִּכּוּרֵי עֲנָבִים, first fruits of grapes) — the timing of the mission: the season of first-ripe grapes means maximum display of the land's fruitfulness.</p>",
        "21": "<p>They surveyed from the wilderness of Zin to Rehob (in the far north): <span class='term'>meˀarets Zin ˁad-Rehov</span>. The full north-south extent of the land — from the Negev to the Syrian border — is covered. The survey is exhaustive; no part of the promised territory is unexamined. The faithless report is not a product of incomplete information.</p>",
        "22": "<p><span class='term'>weˀaḥiman Sheshai weTalmay yaldey haˀanaq</span> — they saw the Anakim (descendants of Anak) in Hebron. The Anakim are the first appearance of the giant-warrior threat that will recur in the spy report. Hebron is specifically mentioned — the very city associated with Abraham's burial place (Gen 23) and David's early capital. The land of the covenant is inhabited by giants.</p>",
        "23": "<p><span class='term'>eshkol ˁanabim ˀeḥad</span> (אֶשְׁכּוֹל עֲנָבִים אֶחָד, a single cluster of grapes) carried on a pole by two men. <em>Eshkol</em> (cluster) names the valley (Nahal Eshkol, Valley of the Cluster). The image of two men carrying a single grape cluster on a pole between them has often been read typologically: the cluster as a type of Christ's fruitfulness (John 15:5), and the carrying between two men as a figure of the cross (the pole between the two bearers). The pomegranates and figs complete the three-fruit witness to the land's abundance.</p>",
        "24": "<p>The valley is named <span class='term'>Eshkol</span> from <span class='term'>ˀeshkol</span> (cluster). Place-naming from events is the standard Israelite aetiological pattern (as at Taberah, Kibroth-hattaavah). The land names its own fruitfulness; the geography testifies to the promise's truth even when the people deny it.</p>",
        "25": "<p><span class='term'>miqets arbaˁim yom</span> (מִקֵּץ אַרְבָּעִים יוֹם) — after forty days. The forty-day period will become forty years of wandering (14:34 — a year for each day). The proportion between the scouting period and the punishment period makes the wandering a measured divine response: each day of faithless observation becomes a year of wilderness existence.</p>",
        "26": "<p>The spies return to Moses, Aaron, and the whole congregation at Kadesh in the wilderness of Paran. <span class='term'>wayashivu ˀotam davarin</span> (וַיָּשִׁיבוּ אוֹתָם דָּבָר) — 'they brought back a word/report to them.' The <em>davar</em> (word, report) is the pivot of the narrative. The same word: the land will be characterized by the word spoken about it, not only by its objective reality.</p>",
        "27": "<p><span class='term'>zavet ḥalav udˀvash</span> (זָבַת חָלָב וּדְבַשׁ, flowing with milk and honey) — the land is exactly what YHWH promised. The spies confirm the divine description (Ex 3:8). <span class='term'>we-ˀefes</span> (וְאֶפֶס — but, nevertheless, however) introduces the reversal: everything good that was promised is true AND (the adversative conjunction of fear) the inhabitants are powerful. The truth of the promise and the reality of the obstacle are both confirmed; the spies fail in the third step — drawing the conclusion of faith.</p>",
        "28": "<p><span class='term'>ˁarim betsurot gedolot meˀod</span> (עָרִים בְּצֻרוֹת גְּדֹלוֹת מְאֹד, large, fortified cities, very great) — the report of military strength. The fortifications are real. The grasshopper report is not based on false intelligence; it is a theological failure of inference. Correct data + wrong theology = faithless conclusion.</p>",
        "29": "<p>Geographic distribution of the enemies: Amalek in the Negev, Hittites/Jebusites/Amorites in the hill country, Canaanites by the sea and the Jordan. The enemy list is comprehensive — every direction, every terrain type is occupied by someone powerful. The land is surrounded; there is no unguarded approach. From a purely human military assessment, the situation is hopeless.</p>",
        "30": "<p><span class='term'>wayyas Kalev ˀet-haˁam</span> (וַיַּהַס כָּלֵב אֶת-הָעָם) — 'Caleb silenced the people.' <em>Hush</em> (הוּשׁ) = to silence, hush. Caleb's intervention is a single act of faith against a rising tide of despair. <span class='term'>ˁaloh naˁaleh</span> (עָלֹה נַעֲלֶה, we shall certainly go up) — the infinitive absolute + imperfect = emphatic certainty. 'We can certainly take it' is the only grammatically emphatically positive statement in the entire spy report.</p>",
        "31": "<p><span class='term'>loˀ nukhal laˁalot</span> (לֹא נוּכַל לַעֲלוֹת, we are not able to go up) — the direct counter to Caleb's emphatic <em>ˁaloh naˁaleh</em>. The same verb (<em>ˁalah</em>, to go up) but with <em>loˀ nukhal</em> (we cannot) rather than the emphatic infinitive absolute. Caleb's 'we certainly can' meets the majority's 'we certainly cannot.' The theological question is not military but about the nature of YHWH's power and promise.</p>",
        "32": "<p><span class='term'>dibbat haˀarets</span> (דִּבַּת הָאָרֶץ, evil report of the land) — literally 'the whispering/slander of the land.' <em>Dibbah</em> is the word for slander, false report, defamation. The ten spies' report is characterized as <em>dibbah</em> — not merely mistaken assessment but a false accusation against the land (and ultimately against YHWH who promised it). <span class='term'>ˀerets ˀokhelet yoshˁeha</span> (land that devours its inhabitants) — a land characterized as consuming those who live in it; the exact opposite of the milk-and-honey description.</p>",
        "33": "<p><span class='term'>Nephilim</span> (נְפִילִים) — from <em>naphal</em> (to fall). The same word as Gen 6:4. The connection to the pre-flood giants frames the Anakim as a pre-diluvian category of threat — something that survived the flood. <span class='term'>ḥagavim</span> (חֲגָבִים, grasshoppers/locusts) — the self-description of the spies. The word is used for locusts (Lev 11:22; Qoh 12:5; Isa 40:22). To describe themselves as grasshoppers before the Anakim is to describe themselves as prey. <span class='term'>weˀen ˀanaḥnu bˀeyneyhem</span> (וְכֵן הָיִינוּ בְּעֵינֵיהֶם, we seemed so in their eyes) — the psychological self-diminishment becomes the assumed perception of the enemy. Fear projects its smallness onto the adversary.</p>",
    },
}


def main():
    data = load_comm("mkt-original", "numbers")
    merge_comm(data, NUMBERS)
    save_comm("mkt-original", "numbers", data)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
